AGI - A stage east of Khan Yunis, in the south of the Gaza Strip, and a banner where photos of the killed prisoners appear. Above them, an image of Israeli premier Benjamin Netanyahu depicted as a vampiro>.&nbsp; To accompany everything there is the written in Arabic, English and Hebrew: "The Netanyahu war criminal and his army killed them with Zionist missiles and war planes." It is the stage set this morning by the militiamen of Hamas who returned the bodies of&nbsp;Shiri Bibas, of the two sons Ariel and Kfir, and of Oded Lifshitz. Before delivery to the Red Cross that will bring the psalms to the IDF troops, the four coffins were exposed on stage.
<div </div
&nbsp;
After receiving the bodies, the army, in turn will perform a short military ceremony led by the chief rabbi of the IDF, before carrying the hostages killed at the Abu Kabir Forensic Institute. The identification process may take up to 48 hours. The son of Oded Lifshitz, whose body is among the ones returned today, spoke of "travelty and tragic deaths, without their families beside them". "This anger will accompany us forever," said Yitzhar Lifshitz on the army radio, "today it does not end for anyone, even if the end is tragic. We continue to pray for the hostages and falls that still have to be returned." Lifshitz, who was 83, was kidnapped by his house in the kibbutz Nir Oz. His wife, Yocheved, was released by&nbsp;Hamas&nbsp;16 days later.
From this morning, 70 of the 251 hostages kidnapped by &nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; on October 7 they are still in Gaza, including the bodies of at least 35 confirmed deaths.&nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; has so far released 24 hostages, 14 Israeli civilians, five soldiers and five Thai citizens. The terrorist group released 105 civilians during a one-week break at the end of November 2023 and four hostages had been released before then. Eight hostages were rescued by the Idf and the bodies of 40 hostages were recovered, including three killed by mistake by the Israeli army while trying to escape their kidnappers.>&nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; is also holding two Israeli civilians who entered the Strip in 2014 and 2015, as well as the body of a soldier killed in 2014. The body of another soldier, also killed in 2014, was recovered in Gaza in January.
<div </div
"Agonia. Pain. There are no words. The hearts of a whole nation are in pieces": is the message on X of Israeli President Isaac&nbsp;Herzog&nbsp; after Hamas has returned the bodies of four hostages. "On behalf of the State of Israel, I call my head and ask forgiveness. They lose for not protecting you on that terrible day.> They lose for not bringing you home safely," added the head of state.&nbsp;
